				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Emilio Bot&iacute;n, Who Built Up Santander Bank, Dies at 79</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Raphael Minder			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-09-10T07:52:02+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 10, 2014 3:52 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 10, 2014 3:52 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/11/business/BOTIN-obit/BOTIN-obit-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/11/business/BOTIN-obit/BOTIN-obit-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/09/11/business/BOTIN-obit/BOTIN-obit-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003106491" width="592" height="361" alt="Under Mr. BotÃ­n, Banco Santanderâs assets rose to 1.1 trillion euros ($1.42 trillion) last year from 20 billion euros in 1998."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="361"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Under Mr. BotÃ­n, Banco Santanderâs assets rose to 1.1 trillion euros ($1.42 trillion) last year from 20 billion euros in 1998.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Juan Manuel Serrano Arce/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/09/10/banco-santander-chairman-emilio-botn-dies-at-age-79/" data-title="Emilio Bot&iacute;n, Who Built Up Santander Bank, Dies at 79" data-description="Mr. BotÃ­n, one of Spain&#039;s most influential businessmen, had led the bank since 1986 and oversaw its growth from a small lender in Spain to one of Europe&#039;s largest banks.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t20h27s" class="update">Updated, 8:27 p.m. | </span><a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/b/emilio_botin/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Emilio Botin.">Emilio BotÃ­n</a>, who transformed Banco Santander from a regional, family-controlled bank into one of Europeâs largest financial institutions, died on Tuesday at his home outside Madrid. He was 79.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank confirmed the death in a statement on Wednesday, saying Mr. BotÃ­n had had a heart attack. Mr. BotÃ­n, whose personal wealth was estimated by Forbes magazine at $1.1 billion, lived in Somosaguas, a wealthy district in Pozuelo de AlarcÃ³n, a suburb of Madrid.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. BotÃ­n ran Banco Santander for three decades after succeeding his father as executive chairman in 1986, continuing a family dynasty at the bank that began in 1909, when his grandfather became chairman. Both father and grandfather were also named Emilio.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Once in charge, Mr. BotÃ­n caught his domestic rivals flat-footed by raising the interest paid on deposits at his bank, a move that greatly increased the market share for what had been a middle-of-the-pack institution with almost no international presence.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then, in a spate of deal making, Mr. BotÃ­n went from one takeover to the next, maintaining a rapid acquisition pace even during the early stages of the financial crisis in 2008. Banco Santanderâs assets soared from 20 billion euros in 1998 to 1.1 trillion euros ($1.42 trillion) at the end of last year, which is about the value of Spainâs gross domestic product.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Besides Spain, Santander now has a huge commercial banking presence in Brazil and Britain, as well as a sizable one in the United States after its takeover of Sovereign Bank, based in Philadelphia. (Sovereign changed its name to Santander Bank in 2013 and is now based in Boston.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Its ability to merge and grow made Santander the envy of banks worldwide, even if the expansion involved some risky bets. Among them was Mr. BotÃ­nâs decision to focus on Brazil even after the 2002 election of Luis InÃ¡cio Lula da Silva, a former trade unionist who some feared would turn against banks. Banco Santander now earns about a quarter of its profit from Brazil.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. BotÃ­nâs track record allowed him to retain almost unchallenged leadership of the bank, even as its expansion and takeovers diluted his family stake to about 2 percent of the equity.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Wednesday, the board of Banco Santander unanimously appointed Mr. BotÃ­nâs daughter Ana Patricia BotÃ­n its next executive chairwoman. Ms. BotÃ­n, 53, started as an investment banker at <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=JPM&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about JPMorgan Chase &#038; Company">JPMorgan Chase</a> in New York before returning to Spain and taking charge of Banesto, a failed Spanish bank that her father took over in a state auction in 1994. More recently, Ms. BotÃ­n was based in London, where she was in charge of the bankâs British operations.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In contrast to bankers in other European countries, where they are largely anonymous figures, Mr. BotÃ­n wielded an almost cultlike influence in Spain. Although he avoided social events and made relatively few public utterances, his comments made headlines.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For example, his pronouncement that the Spanish economy was on the mend was regarded as a crucial vote of confidence in support of Prime Minister JosÃ© Luis RodrÃ­guez Zapateroâs re-election bid in 2008.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In an online article on Wednesday in El PaÃ­s, Spainâs leading daily newspaper, Luis de Guindos, Spainâs economy minister, revealed that Mr. BotÃ­nâs support had been important in the governmentâs decision not to negotiate a full government bailout with international creditors in 2012, shortly after Spain was forced to seek European rescue money for Bankia and other suffering savings banks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. de Guindos wrote that while under intense pressure to opt for a bailout, he received a phone call from Mr. BotÃ­n telling him to resist. âYou know what you have to do and I will back you,â he quoted Mr. BotÃ­n as saying.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As Mr. BotÃ­n integrated his various acquisitions, replacing well-known brands like Banesto and Abbey National with that of Santander, he insisted that employees wear the bankâs signature red â ties for men, scarves for women â on public occasions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Emilio BotÃ­n-Sanz de Sautuola y GarcÃ­a de los RÃ­os was born on Oct. 1, 1934, in Santander, a resort town on the northern coast, where his familyâs bank was headquartered. (It is now based outside Madrid.) The town was once the summer vacation spot of the Spanish royal family.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By royal decree, Queen Isabel II authorized the bankâs founding in 1857, mainly to help finance maritime trade between Spain and Latin America.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. BotÃ­n studied law and then economics before joining the bank at 24 and beginning a rise through the executive ranks. He was in his early 50s when he took over from his father, in 1986, a moment that coincided with Spainâs joining the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_union/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the European Union.">European Union</a>, which brought in substantial European subsidies to modernize Spainâs economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the last three years, Mr. BotÃ­n kept Banco Santander on the sidelines of a Spanish consolidation process in which suffering savings banks that received bailout money were then absorbed by healthier commercial banks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In 2011, as Spainâs banking crisis was nearing its peak, it was revealed that Mr. BotÃ­n and his family were the target of a tax investigation that ended when the family agreed to pay about 200 million euros, now equivalent to about $258 million, in back taxes to avoid tax evasion charges.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While little was disclosed about the settlement, investigators said the familyâs undeclared money had originated in a Swiss bank account that Mr. BotÃ­nâs father had opened after leaving Spain with part of his wealth in late 1936, after the onset of the Spanish Civil War.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In addition to his daughter Ana Patricia, Mr. BotÃ­nâs survivors include his wife, Paloma OâShea, a classical pianist, patron of the arts and founder of the Queen SofÃ­a College of Music in Madrid; and five other children, Carmen, Emilio, Carolina, Paloma and Francisco Javier. Spanish news media said he had 17 grandchildren. Even after turning his bank into an international behemoth, Mr. BotÃ­n remained loyal to the managers who had helped run the family business when it was virtually unknown outside Spain, said Manuel Romera, a finance professor at the IE business school in Madrid.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. BotÃ­nâs management team, Mr. Romera said, was âa bit like a Pretorian guard of people whom he has trusted for many years, and who are very Spanish.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Chad Bray contributed reporting from London.   </em></p>
